Summarizing Discrete outcomes

  • Lets start by thinking about a simple situation where you have a binary exposure, and a binary outcome.

  • In the data set below, I simulate 500 people with a binary outcome. The exposure is relatively uncommon, with a ratio of three to one, unexposed to exposed. The exposure is also related to the outcome. The risk of the event is 0.35 in the unexposed, and 0.15 in the exposed. Due to random sampling variation the sample probabilities will be slightly different.

library(data.table)
# simulate some simple exposure/outcome data:
set.seed(42)
n_people <- 500
exposure <- 
  sample(0:1,n_people,replace=T,prob=c(3,1))
outcome <- 
  rbinom(n=n_people, 
         size=1,
         prob=0.35 + 0.15*exposure)
# create table
df1 <- 
  data.table(exposure=ifelse(exposure==1,'yes','no'),
             outcome=ifelse(outcome==1,'yes','no'))
head(df1)
##    exposure outcome
## 1:      yes      no
## 2:      yes      no
## 3:       no      no
## 4:      yes     yes
## 5:       no      no
## 6:       no     yes
  • Now lets take a moment to examine the overall event rate , and also the event rate by exposure. As expected, we see there is a difference in the probability of having the event depending on whether or not you had the exposure.
# Investigate event rate and exposure
df1[,list(event_rate=sum(outcome=='yes')/.N)]
##    event_rate
## 1:      0.366
df1[,list(event_rate=sum(outcome=='yes')/.N),
    by=exposure]
##    exposure event_rate
## 1:      yes  0.4262295
## 2:       no  0.3465608
  • But, how do we summarize this difference? Theres actually multiple different options and I want to go over them. Its important to note that we are about to see different ways of summarizing the exact same actual situation. At the end of the day, the difference in event probabilities across exposure is what we just found above .

Different ways to summarize the same difference in risk.

  • We focus on three different ways to summarize this difference in risk of the outcome. The first way is the absolute risk difference. the second way is the ratio of the risks. The third way is called the odds ratio.

  • We can summarize the risk difference simply by subtracting the risk of the outcome like so:

results1 <- 
  df1[,list(event_rate=sum(outcome=='yes')/.N),
    by=exposure]
# absolute difference in exposure
results1[exposure=='yes',event_rate] - results1[exposure=='no',event_rate]
## [1] 0.07966866

  • This is interpreted as the absolute difference in risk. If you are exposed, your absolute risk of the outcome is ~8% higher.

  • The second way is the risk ratio. We calculate this by looking at the ratio of the outcome risk between exposed and unexposed like so:

# risk ratio in exposure
results1[exposure=='yes',event_rate]/results1[exposure=='no',event_rate]
## [1] 1.229884
# could also calculate it this way:
1 + (results1[exposure=='yes',event_rate]-results1[exposure=='no',event_rate]) / results1[exposure=='no',event_rate]
## [1] 1.229884

  • this is a relative risk measure - so we interpret this as a percent increase in risk. Those with exposure have a 23% higher risk than those without.

  • The final risk expression is an odds ratio. The odds of an event is the number of events divided by the number of non events (as opposed to the number of events divided by the total!). We calculate the odds of the event in both exposed and unexposed groups, then compare the ratio of those odds (called the odds ratio).

### odds and odds ratio
# odds of getting disease in exposure == no
odds_no <-
  df1[exposure=='no', 
    sum(outcome=='yes')/sum(outcome=='no')]
cat('\nThe odds of the outcome in the unexposed group is: ',odds_no)
## 
## The odds of the outcome in the unexposed group is:  0.5303644
# odds of getting disease in exposure == yes
odds_yes <-
  df1[exposure=='yes', 
    sum(outcome=='yes')/sum(outcome=='no')]
cat('\nThe odds of the outcome in the exposed group is: ',odds_yes)
## 
## The odds of the outcome in the exposed group is:  0.7428571
# odds ratio (ratio of those odds)
cat('\nThe ratio of those odds is: ',odds_yes/odds_no)
## 
## The ratio of those odds is:  1.400654

  • We then interpret this by saying the odds of the outcome in the exposed group are 1.4 times the odds of the outcome in the unexposed group.

  • Why do we have all these ways to summarize risk? They seem to tell a different story, even though the underlying data is the same. We are about to learn logistic regression. The natural interpretation of logistic regression will use odds ratios, so keep that in mind as we fit the models.

General Linear Regression

  • We can generalize the ordinary linear model to a more flexible framework
  • In regular regression, the predictor variables are on the same scale as the outcome.
  • This is often written out in the following form:

\[ E(Y) = B_{0} + B_{1}*X_{1} + B_{2}*X_{2} + ... + B_{k}*X_{k} + e \]

  • We could also write out this model using the distribution and matrix notation.
  • We are assuming the \(E(Y)\) follows a normal distribution, with a linear combination of predictors defining the mean, and the variance defined by \(sigma\).

\[ E(Y) \sim \text{Normal}(\mathbf X \beta,\sigma^2) \]

  • Note that if we used a linear model with a binary outcome, we would be estimating absolute risk difference with the beta parameters!

  • A more general framework would be to allow some function to link the predictors to the outcome, and allow different distributions other than the Normal distribution.

  • We call this function the link function.In normal regression it is simply the identity function.

  • We can also consider different distributional families for the outcome

  • The combination of the link function and the distributional family is the general linear model.

Logistic Regression

\[ln(\frac{P}{1-P}) = B_{0} + B_{1}*X_{1} + B_{2}*X_{2} + ... + B_{k}*X_{k}\]

  • In logistic regression, we are modeling a binary process, so the outcome takes on 1 of 2 possible values
  • The distributional family we use is the binomial distribution, so we assume the outcome follows a binomial distribution
  • The main parameter of interest is \(p\), the probability of the outcome occurrence
  • We use a function called the logit function to link the additive predictor variables to the parameter \(p\)
  • Thus, our predictor variables are on the logit scale, not on the outcome (\(p\)) scale!
  • Logistic regression results are often reported as odds ratios, although we do not have to do that.

Logistic Regression

\[ln(\frac{P}{1-P}) = B_{0} + B_{1}*X_{1} + B_{2}*X_{2} + ... + B_{k}*X_{k}\]

  • What is our target of inference in this model?
    • P the probability of an event occurring
  • Where is the error term?

The logit function

  • In normal regression, the x and y variables are on the same scale
# normal scale 
x = -10:10 
y = x 
plot(x,y)

The logit function

  • In logistic regression, the x and y variables are related by the logit function
# normal scale 
# logit scale 
y=plogis(x) 
plot(x,y)

- Notice the boundaries of the transformation are 0 and 1, so we would not expect to predict any values smaller than 0 or higher than 1. This is a good trait for an estimator that will be predicting p, the probability of success in the binomial distribution.

We can use this function to move from the scale of the betas (inference equation) to the scale of the predicted probability of p.We will come back to this later using data.

The logit function

In logistic regression, the x and y variables are related by the logit function.

\[ ln(\frac{p}{(1-p)})=X \]

With a little algebra you could prove the inverse of the logit function is the following:

\[ p = \frac{exp(x)}{(1+exp(x))} \]

  • Note we can use the plogis and qlogis functions to go from the predictors to the outcome or vice versa
# Outcome p = 0.2 to the betas 
qlogis(.2) 
## [1] -1.386294
# Predictors (Beta) to the probability 
plogis(1) 
## [1] 0.7310586

The glm function

  • We use the glm function for general linear models
  • We must specify the link function and the distribution
  • A variety of models can be fit in this family
  • Normal: link = identity, family=Gaussian
  • Logistic: link = logit, family=binomial
  • Poisson: link = log, family=poisson
  • Gamma: link = log, family=Gamma
  • check the help for family and glm for more details
# sample logistic regression code 
# don't run this code!
# glm(cancer ~ gender + smoking, 
#     data=mydata, 
#     family = binomial(link="logit"))

You can generalize this setup to any situation with a binary outcome, such as estimating the probability of a customer filing a warranty claim, or perhaps the probability of a transaction being fraudulent.

Sales Data Outcome

The outcome of interest is sale, an indicator of if the customer purchased something. We should start by examining this variable and thinking about what a basic model would look like. If we are estimating the probability of the outcome == Yes, where should we start?

# sale prob
sale_df[,sum(sale=='Yes')/.N]
## [1] 0.595625

We can start by estimating the overall probability of observing outcome == yes. In this case it is .596. In the absence of any other information, we might expect the probability of observing the outcome to be 59.6%

This is called the null model, or the intercept only model. We have no predictors in the model, only a single intercept.

\[ ln(\frac{p}{(1-p)})=\beta_0\]

Where p is the probability of observing outcome == yes.

We can actually estimate this basic model using a logistic regression, and then map the resulting parameter estimates.

Fit basic logit model

  • We fit the simple logistic regression below:
# fit null model
mod0 <- 
  glm(sale=='Yes' ~ 1,
      family = binomial(link = "logit"),
      data=sale_df)
summary(mod0)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = sale == "Yes" ~ 1, family = binomial(link = "logit"), 
##     data = sale_df)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##    Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max  
## -1.346  -1.346   1.018   1.018   1.018  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept)  0.38727    0.02278      17   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 10796  on 7999  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 10796  on 7999  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 10798
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

Lets examine these results to further understand the model we just fit:

\[ ln(\frac{p}{(1-p)})=\beta_0\]

The intercept was estimated to be 0.387, so

\[ ln(\frac{p}{(1-p)})=0.387\]

We can use the reverse logit function by solving for p

\[ p = \frac{exp(0.387)}{(1+exp(0.387))} \]

plogis(0.387)
## [1] 0.5955603

And we have recovered the estimate of p, the probability of observing the outcome. Do you see the connection? Lets add some predictors

Logistic Regression with Predictors

We can add predictors into our logistic regression to explore the relationship between the inputs and the outcome. Lets start with another categorical predictor, smoke. First, we create a table of the probabilities of the outcome being observed in each of the predictor categories.

# calculate prob of outcome by group
sale_df[,list(outcome_prob=sum(sale=='Yes')/.N),
        by=gender]
##    gender outcome_prob
## 1:   Male    0.5659867
## 2: Female    0.6401752

This table is telling me that the probability of observing the outcome in the gender == male group is 0.565, while the probability of observing the outcome in the gender == female group is 0.64. It seems like these variables are related. How would you summarize that difference in risk though?

You could summarize is using absolute difference:

# absolute difference in risk
0.64-0.56
## [1] 0.08

Or you could summarize it with a risk ratio:

# ratio of risks
0.64/0.56
## [1] 1.142857

But recall that logistic regression lends itself to an odds ratio:

# odds ratio
(0.64/(1-0.64))/
  (0.56/(1-0.56))
## [1] 1.396825

Fitting a Logistic regression on this data

We can fit a logistic regression with gender as a predictor like so:

# fit  model
mod1 <- 
  glm(sale=='Yes' ~ gender,
      family = binomial(link = "logit"),
      data=sale_df)
summary(mod1)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = sale == "Yes" ~ gender, family = binomial(link = "logit"), 
##     data = sale_df)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max  
## -1.4298  -1.2920   0.9445   1.0669   1.0669  
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error z value Pr(>|z|)    
## (Intercept)  0.57612    0.03686  15.632  < 2e-16 ***
## genderMale  -0.31063    0.04697  -6.614 3.74e-11 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## (Dispersion parameter for binomial family taken to be 1)
## 
##     Null deviance: 10796  on 7999  degrees of freedom
## Residual deviance: 10752  on 7998  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 10756
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

The model we just fit is this:

\[ ln(\frac{p}{(1-p)})=\beta_0 + \beta_1*(gender == male)\]

The parameter estimates are this:

\[ ln(\frac{p}{(1-p)})=0.5761 - 0.3106*(gender == male)\]

Thus, the probability of outcome == Yes for a male is this:

\[ p=rev\_logit(0.5761 - 0.3106*(1))\]

# prob of outcome in male:
plogis(0.5761 - 0.3106*(1))
## [1] 0.5659878

And the probability of outcome == Yes for a female is this:

\[ p=rev\_logit(0.5761 - 0.3106*(1)*(0))\]

# prob of outcome in female
plogis(0.5761 - 0.3106*(1)*(0))
## [1] 0.6401695

Which is exactly what we found above! The p-value for the coefficient is 0.028, which is statistically significant if we use the 0.05 cutoff level. Thus, we find evidence that gender is a risk factor for the sales outcome.

So what about the odds ratios? We can obtain the odds ratios simply by exponentiation of the beta.

# calculate odds ratio for gender == male versus female and sales
exp(-0.31063)
## [1] 0.732985

This is equal to the odds ratio we calculated before:

# odds ratio
(0.5659/(1-0.5659)) / 
  (0.6401/(1-0.6401))
## [1] 0.7329662

Do you understand the connection?

But what about confidence intervals? We can calculate confidence intervals with a code pattern like this:

# get estimate and confidence intervals and exp the result
exp(cbind(estimate=coef(mod1),
          confint(mod1)))
##              estimate     2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 1.7791304 1.6555372 1.9128846
## genderMale  0.7329855 0.6684407 0.8035652

The intercept is not interpretable here, but the Gender Male estimate effect is!

Fitting Multiple Predictors

We can fit multiple predictors and perform regression as we have previously learned in the linear model case. Lets include age as a predictor as well.

# fit  model
mod2 <- 
  glm(sale=='Yes' ~ gender + age,
      family = binomial(link = "logit"),
      data=sale_df)
summary(mod2)
##

This model is telling me that age is a significant predictor of the outcome, after adjusting for gender status. I conclude this based on the p-value of 0.001, which is below my 0.05 cutoff.

Quick review check - what is the null hypothesis being tested here for the conclusion I just made?

Predictions from Logistic Regression

We can score a new dataset using our model, and get a predicted probability of the outcome for a given row of data, considering the model we just fit. In this case we need a new dataset to score.

## create dataset to make predictions on
pred_dataset <-
  CJ(gender=c('Male','Female'),
   age=c(30,50,70))
pred_dataset
##    gender age
## 1: Female  30
## 2: Female  50
## 3: Female  70
## 4:   Male  30
## 5:   Male  50
## 6:   Male  70
## score the dataset
predict(mod2,
        newdata = pred_dataset)
##           1           2           3           4           5           6 
## -0.03294356  0.31792928  0.66880212 -0.17521706  0.17565578  0.52652863

What are these predictions? They are actually on the scale of the betas! If we want to transform them to probabilities, we need the reverse logit function:

plogis(predict(mod2,
               newdata = pred_dataset))
##         1         2         3         4         5         6 
## 0.4917649 0.5788195 0.6612349 0.4563075 0.5438014 0.6286731

Or we can actually just tell the predict() function to make the prediction on the scale of the probs.

# predictions for p
predict(mod2,
        newdata = pred_dataset,
        type = 'response')
##         1         2         3         4         5         6 
## 0.4917649 0.5788195 0.6612349 0.4563075 0.5438014 0.6286731

And add them into the dataset:

# make predictions and add to dataset
pred_dataset[,pred_p:=predict(mod2,
                              newdata = pred_dataset,
                              type = 'response')]
pred_dataset
##    gender age    pred_p
## 1: Female  30 0.4917649
## 2: Female  50 0.5788195
## 3: Female  70 0.6612349
## 4:   Male  30 0.4563075
## 5:   Male  50 0.5438014
## 6:   Male  70 0.6286731

Now we can graph the predictions!

# Visualize these model results
ggplot(pred_dataset, 
       aes(x=age, y=pred_p, color=gender)) + 
  geom_point()

Model predictions for each person in the dataset

  • Lets try to make a plot of age versus sale. We end up with an odd plot - Sale only has values for 1 and 0!

# what do I make of this?
ggplot(sale_df,
       aes(x=age,y=as.integer(sale=='Yes'))) + 
         geom_point()

  • If we add a geom_smooth to this plot, we start to get an idea of the shape. But is the linear form of age appropriate?
# what do I make of this?
ggplot(sale_df,
       aes(x=age,y=as.integer(sale=='Yes'))) + 
         geom_point() + geom_smooth()

# examine the residuals
qplot(residuals(mod3, type='response'))

# plot against age?
qplot(mod3$model$age,residuals(mod3, type='response')) + 
  geom_smooth()

  • These can be challenging to interpret! It looks like there is no systematic pattern to the residuals however - since there is a flat line across the middle. This indicates to me we likely have a good fit with the linear model.

  • Howeverwe could always do this check through the model and test a polynomial relationship:

# fit  model
mod4 <- 
  glm(sale=='Yes' ~ age + I(age**2),
      family = binomial(link = "logit"),
      data=sale_df)
summary(mod4)

Final Model and predictions

  • Lets fit a new model with just those terms, then make predictions for each person and explore them:
# fancy code to construct this from the other object!
var_names <- 
  row.names(res1[res1$`Pr(>Chisq)` < 0.2,])
# create formula
form1 <- 
  as.Formula(paste('sale =="Yes" ~ ',paste(var_names,collapse = ' + ')))

# pass formula into model!
mod6 <- 
  glm(form1,
      family = binomial(link = "logit"),
      data=sale_df)
summary(mod6)

Conclusion

  • In this lecture you learned how logistic regression works and received a comprehensive overview of logistic regression.
  • We started with understanding the general linear model (extensions to normal regression).
  • We next reviewed the logit function to understand how the linear combination of predictors is connected to the outcome.
  • We implemented increasingly complex logistic regression parameterizations and reviewed how to develop and interpret these models.
  • You learned how to score new data in addition to the old data in the model.
